Abstract = {{We examine the role of language analytical ability, one of the
   components of language aptitude a specific ability for learning
   languages - during acquisition of a novel grammar. We investigated
   whether the neural basis of Artificial Grammar Learning (AGL) differs
   between populations of highly and moderately skilled learners.
   Participants performed an AGL task during an fMRI scan and data from
   task's test phases were analysed. Highly skilled learners performed
   better than moderately skilled ones and engaged during the task more
   neural resources in the right hemisphere, i.e. in the right
   angular/supramarginal gyrus and superior frontal and middle frontal
   gyrus and in the posterior cingulate gyrus. Additional analyses
   investigating the temporal dynamics of brain activity during learning
   revealed lateralisation differences in the modulation of activity in the
   parietal and temporal cortex. In particular, the left angular gyrus BOLD
   activity was coupled with high performance on the AGL task and with a
   steep learning curve.}},
