Volume = {{7}},
Month = {{MAR 21}},
Abstract = {{Clinical data have been equivocal and controversial as to the benefits
   to the brain and cognition of hormone therapy (HT) in postmenopausal
   women. Recent reevaluation of the role of estrogens proposed that HT may
   effectively prevent the deleterious effects of aging on cognition, and
   reduces the risks of dementia, including Alzheimer's disease, if
   initiated early at the beginning of menopause. Yet, little is known
   about the effects of HT on brain activation related to cognitive
   control, the ability to make flexible decisions in relation to internal
   goals. Here, we used fMRI to directly test for a modulation of
   sequential 17 beta estradiol (2 mg/day) plus oral progesterone (100
   mg/day) on task switching-related brain activity in women at early
   postmenopause. The results showed that HT enhanced dorsolateral
   prefrontal cortex recruitment during task switching. Between-subjects
   correlation analyses revealed that women who engaged more the
   dorsolateral prefrontal cortex showed higher task switching performance
   after HT administration. These results suggest that HT, when taken early
   at the beginning of postmenopause, may have beneficial effect on
   cognitive control prefrontal mechanisms. Together, these findings
   demonstrate that HT can prevent the appearance of reduced prefrontal
   cortex activity, a neurophysiological measure observed both in healthy
   aging and early dementia.}},
